<header class="header">
  <h1>How to Plan a Garden in a Short Growing Season</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Short seasons require climate-based precision.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, your growing season is bounded by frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
    But in short-season climates, the true constraint is not just when frost begins and ends —
    it’s how much heat accumulates before frost returns.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Counts as a Short Growing Season?</h2>

  <p>
    Frost dates are framed using 1991–2020 climate normals at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    That means your listed frost boundaries represent what typically happens — not a guarantee.
  </p>

  <p>
    A short growing season generally means:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>90–120 frost-free days</li>
    <li>An earlier-than-average first fall frost</li>
    <li>Cool early spring and late fall temperatures</li>
    <li>Lower total accumulated Growing Degree Days (GDD)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    You can determine your local frost window using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    But frost-free days alone do not determine crop success.
    Two locations may both report 110 frost-free days — yet produce very different harvest outcomes.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Real Constraint: The Frost Boundary</h2>

  <p>
    A growing season is bounded by two frost events:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Last spring frost (32°F threshold)</li>
    <li>First fall frost (32°F threshold)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    At the 50% probability level, these dates represent the midpoint of historical outcomes.
    Roughly half of years will experience frost earlier or later than these listed boundaries.
  </p>

  <p>
    Short-season climates compress the time between these frost boundaries.
    But more importantly, they compress the <strong>amount of usable heat</strong> available inside that window.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is why planning must move beyond calendar logic.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Frost-Free Days Aren’t Enough</h2>

  <p>
    Many gardeners rely on “days to maturity.”
    But as explained in
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>,
    development speed depends on temperature — not calendar days alone.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consider two climates with 115 frost-free days:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Climate A accumulates 2,400 GDD (base 50°F).</li>
    <li>Climate B accumulates 1,700 GDD (base 50°F).</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The calendar window appears identical.
    The seasonal heat budget does not.
  </p>

  <p>
    In cooler climates, crops accumulate heat more slowly.
    Even if frost arrives on schedule, insufficient heat accumulation can delay maturity.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Your Seasonal Heat Budget (Growing Degree Days)</h2>

  <p>
    Growing Degree Days measure accumulated heat over time.
    Most warm-season crops use a base temperature of <strong>50°F (10°C)</strong>.
  </p>

  <pre>
GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </pre>

  <p>
    Each day contributes heat units when average temperature exceeds 50°F.
    Over the course of your frost-free window, those units accumulate into your
    <strong>seasonal heat budget</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate how many GDD typically accumulate before first frost using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    For a deeper explanation of how frost timing and heat accumulation interact, see
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short-season climates, total GDD is often the limiting factor —
    not just the number of frost-free days.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Evaluating Crop Feasibility</h2>

  <p>
    Once you know your seasonal heat budget, the next step is comparing it to crop requirements.
  </p>

  <p>
    Crops generally fall into heat-demand tiers:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Low heat demand:</strong> Lettuce, spinach, radishes</li>
    <li><strong>Moderate heat demand:</strong> Bush beans, zucchini</li>
    <li><strong>High heat demand:</strong> Large tomatoes, winter squash, long-season sweet corn</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Within each crop category, varieties differ substantially.
    For example, tomato cultivars can range from roughly 1,200 to over 2,000 GDD.
    See
    <a href="/guides/how-many-growing-degree-days-do-tomatoes-need/">How Many Growing Degree Days Do Tomatoes Need?</a>
    for typical ranges.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your expected seasonal GDD comfortably exceeds a crop’s requirement,
    maturity is likely in a typical year.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your seasonal GDD barely matches the requirement,
    you are operating near the frost boundary with minimal margin.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Risk Margin: Comfortable, Borderline, or Unlikely</h2>

  <p>
    Because frost dates use probability framing,
    actual seasonal heat varies year to year.
  </p>

  <p>
    Short-season planning works best when you evaluate risk margin:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Comfortable Margin:</strong> Seasonal GDD exceeds crop requirement by several hundred units.</li>
    <li><strong>Borderline Margin:</strong> Seasonal GDD closely matches crop requirement.</li>
    <li><strong>Unlikely Margin:</strong> Seasonal GDD typically falls short of crop requirement.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Borderline situations are common in short climates.
    This is where variety selection, transplant timing, and microclimate placement matter most.
  </p>

  <p>
    Planning is not about eliminating risk —
    it is about intentionally choosing how much risk to accept.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Applied Scenario Modeling</h2>

  <p>
    Consider three short-season examples:
  </p>

  <p><strong>Scenario 1 — 2,200 GDD Available</strong><br>
  A 1,300 GDD tomato variety has strong margin.<br>
  A 2,100 GDD heirloom operates near the frost boundary.</p>

  <p><strong>Scenario 2 — 1,800 GDD Available</strong><br>
  Short-season sweet corn hybrids (~1,500 GDD) may mature.<br>
  Winter squash requiring 2,200+ GDD becomes unlikely without exceptional warmth.</p>

  <p><strong>Scenario 3 — 1,400 GDD Available</strong><br>
  Cool-season crops thrive.<br>
  High-heat crops become structurally mismatched to the climate.</p>

  <p>
    These differences illustrate why calendar labels like “100 days to maturity”
    can conceal large heat deficits.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Can You Add Effective Season Length?</h2>

  <p>
    In constrained climates, small adjustments may improve risk margin:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Starting seeds indoors to align transplant timing with frost boundaries</li>
    <li>Using warm microclimates near south-facing walls</li>
    <li>Applying lightweight row covers to reduce early fall frost exposure</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If indoor starts shift transplant timing relative to frost risk,
    you can anchor scheduling using the
    <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Start Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    However, season extension methods generally increase protection —
    not total seasonal heat accumulation.
  </p>

  <p>
    They improve margin.
    They do not transform a low-heat climate into a high-heat one.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Short-Season Planning Model</h2>

  <p>
    Planning a garden in a short growing season follows a clear sequence:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Frost → Season Length → Growing Degree Days → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    Step 1: Identify frost boundaries at 32°F (50% probability).<br>
    Step 2: Determine your frost-free window.<br>
    Step 3: Estimate total seasonal GDD before first frost.<br>
    Step 4: Compare crop heat requirements to your heat budget.<br>
    Step 5: Evaluate your margin.
  </p>

  <p>
    When those pieces align, crop maturity becomes predictable in a typical year.
    When they do not, calendar-based planting advice often fails.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Short growing seasons are constrained by frost timing and limited heat accumulation.</li>
    <li>Frost boundaries use a 32°F definition and 50% probability framing.</li>
    <li>Growing Degree Days measure your seasonal heat budget.</li>
    <li>Crop viability depends on whether your heat budget exceeds crop requirements.</li>
    <li>Risk margin determines how predictable maturity is in a typical year.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short climates, successful planning comes from modeling frost boundaries and heat accumulation together —
    not relying on planting calendars alone.
  </p>
</section>